.TH "__bitmap_shift_left" 9 "__bitmap_shift_left" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
__bitmap_shift_left \- logical left shift of the bits in a bitmap
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "void" __bitmap_shift_left
.BI "(unsigned long *dst "  ","
.BI "const unsigned long *src "  ","
.BI "unsigned int shift "  ","
.BI "unsigned int nbits "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "dst" 12
destination bitmap
.IP "src" 12
source bitmap
.IP "shift" 12
shift by this many bits
.IP "nbits" 12
bitmap size, in bits
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Shifting left (multiplying) means moving bits in the LS -> MS
direction.  Zeros are fed into the vacated LS bit positions
and those MS bits shifted off the top are lost.
